Additionally, while titles like "General Campaigning Against the East" or "General Pacifying the East" reflect a Chinese perspective, Wa Zui's title of "General Pacifying the West" indicates a Wa-centric view. This has led to theories proposing a governance structure with two central figures—General Pacifying the East and General Pacifying the West—overseeing generals like General Campaigning Against Rebels and General Assisting the Nation{{Sfn|Kawachi Haruhito|2018|11=73-119}}.

Regarding the {{ill|Five kings of Wa|ja|倭の五王|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, if Chin and Sai are considered separate individuals, it remains unclear how they are related. One theory posits that they represented separate power groups (e.g., Mozu and Furuichi Kofun Groups) and that Sai may have been connected to Wa Zui’s lineage{{Sfn|Kawachi Haruhito|2018|11=73-119}}.

In the recorded articles about the {{ill|Five kings of Wa|ja|倭の五王|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, the only named individuals besides the kings themselves are Wa Zui and {{ill|Sima Cao Da|ja|曹達|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, a retainer of {{ill|San of Wa|ja|讃|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.

