Details about Wa Zui remain unclear, but the shared surname "Wa" with the Wa King suggests that royal family generals were part of the ruling power structure within the {{ill|Yamato kingship|ja|ヤマト王権|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamato kingship|qq=}}.<ref>Sakamoto Yoshitane, "The Five Kings of Wa," in 『{{ill|Kokushi Daijiten|ja|国史大辞典|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kokushi Daijiten|qq=}}』, Yoshikawa Kōbunkan.</ref> Notably, the Rank of General Pacifying the West, similar to General Pacifying the East, only differs by one tier within the third Rank, indicating a hierarchical but parallel relationship<ref name="Mori"/>{{Sfn|Kawachi Haruhito|2018|11=73-119}}. This has led to theories that Wa governance involved co-rule by figures of equal standing, akin to the relationship between {{ill|Himiko|ja|卑弥呼|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Himiko|qq=}} and her brother, reflecting a shared governance model.<ref name="Mori">Mori Kimikazu, 『{{ill|The Five Kings of Wa: 5th-Century East Asia and the Wa Kings|ja|倭の五王 5世紀の東アジアと倭王群像（日本史リブレット 人 002）|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/The Five Kings of Wa: 5th-Century East Asia and the Wa Kings|qq=}}』 Yamakawa Shu11ansha, 2010, 11. 47-50.</ref> This governance model is also compared to the coexistence of Kofuns like the {{ill|Mozu Kofun Group|ja|百舌鳥古墳群|1=Mozu Tombs|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mozu Kofun Group|13=User:Immanuelle/Mozu Tombs|qq=}}, {{ill|Furuichi Kofun Cluster|lt=Furuichi Kofun Cluster|lt=Furuichi Kofun Group|ja|古市古墳群|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Furuichi Kofun Group|qq=}}, or {{ill|Saki Kofun Group|ja|佐紀盾列古墳群|1=Saki Tatenami Kofun group|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Saki Kofun Group|13=User:Immanuelle/Saki Tatenami Kofun group|qq=}}.

Additionally, while titles like "General Campaigning Against the East" or "General Pacifying the East" reflect a Chinese perspective, Wa Zui's title of "General Pacifying the West" indicates a Wa-centric view. This has led to theories proposing a governance structure with two central figures—General Pacifying the East and General Pacifying the West—overseeing generals like General Campaigning Against Rebels and General Assisting the Nation{{Sfn|Kawachi Haruhito|2018|11=73-119}}.

Regarding the {{ill|Five kings of Wa|ja|倭の五王|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Five kings of Wa|qq=}}, if Chin and Sai are considered separate individuals, it remains unclear how they are related. One theory posits that they represented separate power groups (e.g., Mozu and Furuichi Kofun Groups) and that Sai may have been connected to Wa Zui’s lineage{{Sfn|Kawachi Haruhito|2018|11=73-119}}.

In the recorded articles about the {{ill|Five kings of Wa|ja|倭の五王|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Five kings of Wa|qq=}}, the only named individuals besides the kings themselves are Wa Zui and {{ill|Sima Cao Da|ja|曹達|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sima Cao Da|qq=}}, a retainer of {{ill|San of Wa|ja|讃|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/San of Wa|qq=}}.

